I"ÿM<p>5 years ago, I said in one of my articles that I shall return, one day, with a method of <strong>hot patching</strong> functions inside live processes; So‚Ä¶ I guess this is that day.</p>

<p>What we‚Äôll try to achieve here is to <strong>replace</strong>, from outside, a function inside a <strong>running executable</strong>, without stopping/freezing the process (or crashing it‚Ä¶).</p>

<p>In my opinion, applying hot patches is quite a daunting task, if implemented from scratch, since:</p>

<ul>
  <li>it requires access to a different process‚Äô memory (most operating systems are fans of <strong>process isolation</strong>)</li>
  <li>has software compatibility constraints (<strong>Windows</strong> binaries vs <strong>Linux</strong> binaries)</li>
  <li>has architecture compatibility contrains (<strong>32bit</strong> vs <strong>64bit</strong>)</li>
  <li>it implies working with machine code and brings certain issues to the table</li>
  <li>it has only a didactic purpose - probably no one would actually use a ‚Äòfrom-scratch‚Äô method since there are tools that do this better</li>
</ul>

<p>Considering these, I guess it is better to use something that was actually written for this task and not coding something manually.
Therefore, we‚Äôll be looking at a way to do this with <a href="https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/pin-a-dynamic-binary-instrumentation-tool">Intel Pin</a>. I stumbled upon this tool while working at a completely different project but it seems to be quite versatile. Basically, it is described as a <strong>Dynamic Binary Instrumentation Tool</strong>, however we‚Äôll be using it to facilitate the procedure of writing code to another process‚Äô memory.</p>

<h2 id="initial-preparations">Initial Preparations</h2>

<p>Start by <a href="https://software.intel.com/en-us/articles/pin-a-binary-instrumentation-tool-downloads">downloading Intel Pin</a> and extract it somewhere in your workspace.</p>

<h5 id="im-doing-this-tutorial-on-ubuntu-x86_64-but-im-expecting-the-code-to-be-highly-similar-on-windows-or-other-operating-systems">I‚Äôm doing this tutorial on Ubuntu x86_64, but I‚Äôm expecting the code to be highly similar on Windows or other operating systems.</h5>

<p>Now, I imagine this turns out to be useful for endpoints that provide remote services to clients - i.e.: a server receives some sort of input and is expected to also return something. Let‚Äôs say that someone discovered that a¬† service is vulnerable to certain inputs - so it can be comprimised by the first attacker who submits a specially crafted request.¬†We‚Äôll consider that taking the¬†service down,¬†compiling, deploying and¬†launching a new instance is not a desirable solution so hot patching is wanted until a new¬†version is ready.¬†</p>

<p>I‚Äôll use the following <strong>dummy</strong> C program to illustrate the aforementioned model - to keep it simple, I‚Äôm reading inputs from <strong>stdin</strong>¬†(instead of a tcp stream / network).</p>

<figure class="highlight"><pre><code class="language-c" data-lang="c"><table class="rouge-table"><tbody><tr><td class="gutter gl"><pre class="lineno">1
2
3
4
5
6
